<TEXT>
more than 200 bishops from around the world 
gather in rome this weekend for a synod expected to consider the 
issue of sex and the roman catholic priesthood 
pope john paul ii called the assembly of 238 bishops to discuss 
the formation of priests in todays world an advisory body it 
will make recommendations to him at the end of the monthlong 
meeting which starts sunday 
the churchs rules that priests be celibate and foresake 
marriage are not expected to be subjects up for debate according 
to church sources involved in preparations for the meeting john 
paul has shown no indications the rules might be changed under his 
papacy 
but a major concern of the bishops is finding and training 
candidates able to live up to the priestly vows of poverty 
chastity and obedience 
several sexual scandals involving churchmen have made headlines 
in recent months 
the archbishop of atlanta eugene a marino resigned july 10 
after revelations of a twoyear intimate relationship with a 
young woman singer and lay minister 
a report in july by a churchappointed commission in 
newfoundland said priests had sexually abused boys in the canadian 
province for more than a decade and that the church had failed to 
stop it the archbishop alphonsus penney accepted responsibility 
and offered his resignation to the pope 
such inhouse problems are usually handled with great discretion 
by the vatican it has never commented publicly on the marino case 
announcing only that he resigned for reasons of health 
but the vatican has issued several documents this year 
expressing concern over the qualifications of candidates for the 
priesthood particularly at a time when the church is trying to 
increase the number of priests and nuns 
the paper bluntly declared that aspiring priests and nuns must 
overcome sexual desires that would break their vows of chastity 
it said those unable to overcome their homosexual tendencies or 
who maintain it is possible to adopt a third way living in an 
ambiguous state between celibacy and marriage must be dismissed 
from religious life 
and it suggested that psychological testing can be useful in 
determining sexual problems in candidates 
i dont think anyone would say it was easy to be celibate 
said the rev howard bleichner director of the department for 
priestly formation of the national conference of catholic bishops 
in washington dc 
but he said the highly publicized failures of priests did not 
reflect a problem with the nature of the priesthood 
if a prominent man is unfaithful in marriage i wouldnt take 
that as a reason to rethink the institution of marriage 
bleichner said 
while the number of worldwide ordinations has been growing after 
hitting a decade low in 1979 the numbers are still down in the 
united states and western europe 
bleichner said students in the past four years of us seminary 
numbered 3698 this year compared with 7855 in 1968 
the question in our society is of longterm commitment 
examples of that are becoming increasingly rare look at the 
breakup of marriages 
a 1988 report by the us bishops found that many of the 
nations priests were overworked lonely and sexually troubled it 
contended that the mandatory celibacy is a major reason why priests 
leave 
the american bishops bleichner said are looking forward to 
hearing the experiences on priestly training from other countries 
there are clearly great differences in experiences from country 
to country brought home by two bishops attending a vatican news 
conference on the synod 
cardinal lucas moreira neves of sao salvador da bahia brazil 
lamented the frightening lack of priests in his diocese noting 
there were 340 to serve the 3 million people 
bishop henryk myzinski of wloclawek in the popes native poland 
said he had 590 priests for 11 million faithful 
the us bishops will be represented by cardinal joseph 
bernardin of chicago cardinal james hickey of washington dc 
archbishop daniel pilarczyk of cincinnati and bishop john marshall 
of burlington vt who headed a study of us seminaries in the 
early 80s 
the pope who appoints 15 percent of the delegates named bishop 
harry flynn of lafayette la bishop robert brom of san diego and 
bishop donald wuerl of pittsburgh all former seminary rectors 
</TEXT>
