editors note this report is one of a series on the german 
countdown to unity on oct 3 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
as germany rushes toward 
unification it is also becoming the promised land for tens of 
thousands of people swarming into the country to escape poverty in 
the third world and eastern europe 
the influx is further strapping west germany already 
hardpressed to come up with the tens of billions of dollars needed 
to rescue east germany from economic catastrophe 
german unification which will formally take place wednesday 
appears to have given a boost to the pace of arrivals authorities 
expect a record number of 200000 political asylumseekers this 
year last year the figure stood at 120000 
last year west germany became the new home for 350000 ethnic 
german immigrants from eastern europe about 500000 east germans 
resettled across the border in 1989 and in the early months of 
1990 
authorities are aware that many refugees are seeking a brighter 
economic future even if they say they are fleeing political 
persecution 
they are trying to stem the tide but it wont be easy 
all they have to do to stay here is make it believable that 
they are foreign and that they are politically persecuted said 
volker moeser who runs a government reception center just outside 
frankfurt for seekers of political asylum 
the center in schwalbach is housing about 850 refugees and 
dozens of 12bed tents have been put up to deal with the influx 
the opening of east european borders has contributed 
dramatically to the increase 
once registered asylum applicants settle down to wait until 
authorities decide whether to recognize them as political refugees 
a process that can take five years only about 3 percent receive 
refugee status but the statistics dont seem to be a deterrent 
at the schwalbach camps cafeteria poles and romanians mingled 
with turks ghanaians pakistanis somalis afghanis and a variety 
of other nationals as they lined up to buy cheap lunch 
outside a tent a romanian gypsy family of 13 enjoyed a recent 
sunny day by relaxing on a blanket the head of the clan its only 
male made a few declarations of support for the new romanian 
authorities and claims of past persecution by securitate secret 
police 
then he talked about why he really brought the family to 
germany 
one day they closed the factory and i lost my job there is no 
future in romania said the man who gave his name only as 
novakovic and said he was from timisoara 
in the latest twist west germany suddenly faces the prospect of 
soviet deserters as well officials have expressed fears that many 
of the 360000 soviet soldiers stationed in east germany may ask 
for asylum rather than return to a bleak future in their homeland 
as the troops are pulled out under german unification agreements 
eight soviet soldiers deserted in august and 26 more applied for 
asylum in the central hesse state in recent weeks some coming over 
with their wives 
also bonn officials have temporarily halted the immigration of 
soviet jews in order to prevent a virtual stampede the west german 
consulate in kiev alone has received 10000 applications 
the rush of new arrivals from all over is stretching social 
services to the limit communities have been refusing to accept the 
refugees because they lack housing or even sending them to east 
germany 
but east germany itself still has to persuade 80000 workers 
from vietnam cuba and mozambique to return home citizens of east 
bloc countries once had free access to east germany but visa 
requirements have been tightened 
in some third world countries newspapers carry advertisements 
touting the advantages of seeking political asylum in west germany 
the ads are placed by rings that then organize the trips for a 
hefty fee 
some officials think that only legitimate asylumseekers should 
be allowed to cross the borders they also want the paperwork 
speeded up and those refused asylum to be expelled immediately 
the federal governments blueprint calls for aid at the source 
under the proposal germany would help build housing and create 
jobs in poor countries in an attempt to keep potential 
asylumseekers from leaving 
we want a larger germany to remain friendly to foreigners 
said interior minister wolfgang schaeuble 
</TEXT>
