<TEXT>
a section of the berlin wall was installed on 
the campus of westminster college where winston churchill gave his 
famous 1946 speech describing an iron curtain dividing the 
world 
churchills granddaughter edwina sandys used a 32foot wide 
section of the dismantled wall to create a sculpture she calls 
breakthrough 
ms sandys daughter of churchills eldest daughter diane was 
on hand thursday to watch as construction crews used a crane to 
lower slabs of the wall near a statue of her grandfather 
sandys a new york sculptor said she wanted the work at 
westminster because it was here that churchill gave the speech that 
outlined the developing cold war era of eastwest conflict that 
started after world war ii and ended last year 
i feel the wall is really the physical embodiment of the iron 
curtain she said im really pleased to have it here its 
really a perfect fit the whole thing 
first and foremost its a piece of art but also its a 
political statement she said sometimes they intertwine 
churchill came to fulton on march 5 1946 with president 
truman in his speech at westminster he warned of new problems 
facing the world after the allied victory in world war ii 
in the bestknown passage he said a shadow has fallen upon 
the scene so lately lighted by allied victory from stettin 
in the baltic to trieste in the adriatic an iron curtain has 
descended across the continent 
the 10foothigh sculpture has sections cut out in the shape of 
a man and woman through which people can walk one side is covered 
with graffiti left by west berliners after the wall went up in 
1962 
after ms sandys approached east german officials in february 
about her idea for the sculpture they allowed her to survey the 
wall and choose the sections she wanted those she took had been in 
an area frequented by artists she said 
i chose these sections out of 200 she said because i 
thought the colors of the graffiti were dynamic and lovely 
westminster a small liberal arts college in this central 
missouri community of about 11000 has about 750 students 
</TEXT>
