<TEXT>
angelo natale editorial supervisor at the world 
service and foreign desks of the associated press and a former ap 
foreign correspondent has died at the age of 64 
his ap career spanned almost five decades 
natale died at his home in manhattan on wednesday he had 
suffered from chronic diabetes and vascular problems 
natale joined the ap in 1942 and served in a variety of news 
assignments that took him to cairo and moscow as well as to 
several ap bureaus in the eastern united states 
his only time away from the ap was a 20month stint with the 
us army air force during world war ii 
in 1968 natale joined the world service division at ap 
headquarters in new york he was promoted to editorial supervisor 
in 1973 at the desk responsible for transmitting ap news reports to 
8500 subscribers in 105 countries worldwide 
angelo was not only a supervisor but was a friend to everyone 
in the department and to ap people around the world said tom 
kent who is in charge of aps foreign and world service desks 
a native of the bronx natale was educated in new york city 
public schools and went to stuyvesant high school in manhattan he 
entered the city college of new york in september 1941 and then 
went to work for the ap as an office assistant in march 1942 
after military service he returned to the ap in 1945 and worked 
in various clerical positions while attending college at night 
natale was graduated from city college with a bachelor of social 
science degree in 1950 and then became a reporter at aps newark 
bureau 
he became correspondent in atlantic city in 1956 in november 
1956 he entered the aps foreign service in cairo egypt at the 
height of the suez canal crisis he later covered stories 
throughout the middle east 
in early 1958 natale was transferred to the ap bureau in 
moscow and in 1959 he returned to the united states and was 
assigned to aps new haven conn bureau he transferred to the 
world service desk in 1968 
natale is survived by his mother rachel natale and his 
brother salvatore natale 
services are planned for saturday at gleasons funeral home in 
flushing queens burial will follow at mt st mary cemetery in 
flushing 
</TEXT>
