of the center for the study of developing societies 
critics say the timing and manner of announcing the policy made 
it look like a political maneuver to undercut the support of one of 
singhs populist rivals 
the policy is based on a muchcriticized study by an obscure 
politician of low caste bp mandal which languished for 10 years 
until singh revived it in his election platform last year 
the mandal commission classified 3000 castes as socially and 
educationally backward and recommended that 27 percent of 
government jobs be set aside for them the government employs some 
18 million people though the military and defense jobs are 
excluded from the quota system 
previously 22 percent were reserved for the lowest sector of 
society native tribes and untouchables the new policy left 
slightly more than half the jobs available on merit alone 
in a nation where millions of educated indians lack work the 
new quota sent shivers through the college campuses 
if i get 85 percent on my marks and he a lowcaste student 
gets 40 percent he will get the job aggarwal said i work 
very hard i know i must face competition now whats the point 
nandi said only 1700 jobs a year are affected by the government 
plan 
the students are overreacting he saidthe upper castes 
have a feeling of insecurity they are few in number and the lower 
castes are in a great majority 
singh argues his quotas will blur the distinctions of caste 
critics say he has revived the notion of caste as an instrument of 
state policy 
the caste system which began perhaps 2500 years ago 
categorized hindus into a social hierarchy determined by birth and 
sanctioned by religion 
some 20000subcastes derive from the four primary castes the 
brahmins who are priests teachers and astrologers kshariyas who 
comprise the royalty and warrior class vaisya who are merchants 
and traders and sudras who do the menial tasks 
below them all are the untouchables tradition forbids them from 
wearing shoes riding bicycles sharing a water well with caste 
hindus 
modern india which is 82 percent hindu embraced secularism and 
socialist ideals when it became independent from britain in 1947 
and pledged to discard the caste system 
urbanization economic mobility and the growth of a middle class 
have dimmed the traditional power of caste which once dictated who 
one married where one worked and even how one carried himself 
but its power is still considerable weekend classified pages 
publish columns of matrimonial offers based on caste most 
marriages still are arranged by parents 
caste is surviving theres no doubt but the role of caste is 
changing nandi said its not much different than ethnic 
groupings in the united states 
