<TEXT>
an 8000yearold village under the sea 
has yielded an intriguing discovery a water well thought to be the 
oldest in the world 
the archaeologist who found the well says it suggests ancient 
man was smarter than previously thought 
the 6yearold dig beneath the mediterranean seabed has already 
turned up a trove of information about neolithic man findings 
include the remains of stone houses a fireplace preserved with its 
charred wood 23 buried skeletons the bones of the animals the 
villagers ate the seeds they planted the tools they made from 
bone and stone 
the latest excitement is over the discovery of several wells 
one of which was excavated and found to be 16 feet deep 
ehud galili the archaeologist heading the dig said the village 
is 7700 to 8000 years old so that the well is some 1000 years 
older than the oldest well known until now 
it is surprising because for the first time we have figured 
out that prehistoric man was aware of the existence of water tables 
under the ground and was able and had the proper technology to dig 
these wells and to use this fresh water he told reporters 
visiting the site thursday 
as far as i know this is the oldest well discovered from that 
period he said 
it raises fascinating questions how did ancient man know that 
if he dug deep enough he would strike fresh water and where did 
he acquire the skill to sink a round shaft paved with stone in 
much the same way as many modern wells are built 
the well was full of prehistoric trash bones broken tools and 
stones galili said he speculated that at some point its water had 
grown salty and it was turned into a garbage disposal pit 
with the end of the ice age the village disappeared beneath the 
mediterranean as melted ice raised the earths sea levels sea sand 
up to 12 feet thick preserved it 
the village covers about 10 acres and lies beneath 39 feet of 
water about 400 yards off the coast 
it is in a small bay overlooked by a crusader fort at athlit 10 
miles south of the port city of haifa the dig is sponsored by the 
governments antiquities authority 
like many underwater sites off israels coast it came to light 
because the creation of the jewish state in 1948 led to a 
construction boom huge amounts of beach sand were quarried 
depleting the protective layer over the undersea sites 
for archaeologists the underwater location is a cause for 
crises every storm disrupts the ancient undersea world and a 
wall or a skeleton that has lain undisturbed for thousands of years 
can be destroyed in a matter of weeks galili said 
among galilis more striking finds is the skeleton of a woman 
aged about 18 lying in a fetal position her hand making a 
clutching gesture 
nodules in the earholes of some skulls point to the inhabitants 
having been divers since such nodules result from a disease common 
among people who spend too much time under water he said 
galili said marks on the teeth in one skull suggest the man 
worked with ropes using his teeth to help knot them 
while there is no indication the villagers had already 
domesticated animals the seeds found at the site imply that they 
had learned to grow crops galili said 
</TEXT>
