<TEXT>
the united states and the soviet union are close 
to agreement on a new treaty to cut their conventional arms in 
europe 
two of the three remaining disputes were basically resolved 
thursday at a meeting of secretary of state james a baker iii and 
soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze 
that left a disagreement over limiting aircraft to be ironed out 
in time for a 34nation summit in paris in midnovember 
the steady withdrawal of soviet troops and tanks from eastern 
and central europe along with sizable reductions in us forces 
among the nato countries are already accomplishing what the treaty 
negotiators set out to do 
however the accord would make reductions of weapons troops 
are being omitted legally binding and it would be a symbolic 
milestone in the easing of eastwest tensions 
baker and shevardnadze plan to meet again soon in new york to 
chip away at the aircraft issue and to make sure the tentative 
agreements on the two other issues stick 
one would establish zones in which noth atlantic treaty 
organization and warsaw pact arms would be limited the other would 
impose a ceiling on the percentage of either blocs weapons that 
any one nation could retain 
baker said after seeing shevardnadze that they had made some 
good progress toward the treaty the projected centerpiece of the 
34nation summit shevardnadze said they had made real headway 
the treaty between nato and the warsaw pact has been in 
negotiation in vienna since february 1989 an earlier 15year 
attempt to reduce tensions through cutbacks in troops and weapons 
failed 
but when soviet president mikhail s gorbachev set out to end 
the cold war the outlook brightened 
still nagging disputes stood in the way us and soviet 
negotiators racing the clock have been meeting daily since last 
week first in washington and since then in new york 
although the treaty is not complete baker and shevardnadze 
agreed to submit the tentative understandings on two of the three 
most troublesome issues to their allies 
immediately after the session baker briefed nato foreign 
ministers in new york for the special session of the united 
nations general assembly on the results 
a senior state department official told reporters meanwhile 
there was basic agreement with the soviets on establishing 
zones in which numerical limits would be placed on nonnuclear 
weapons 
also baker and shevardnadze tentatively agreed on how high a 
percentage of permissible weapons any one nation could have in its 
arsenal said the official who demanded anonymity 
the third major issue remains unresolved although baker 
volunteered that progress had been made on it 
it concerns whether all european landbased aircraft of the two 
alliances should be included in the treaty as the united states 
has proposed or whether planes the soviets say have defensive 
missions should be exempt 
we have removed most of the gaps the state department 
source said separately 
much of the spadework was done by us and soviet negotiators 
before baker and shevardnadze met 
they are trying to have all key issues settled so the 
painstaking process of preparing a text can begin and be completed 
by the time of the projected summit 
a senior french official briefing american reporters said he 
was confident the treaty would be ready for signing at the paris 
meeting 
one of thursdays breakthroughs concerned what technicians call 
the sufficiency rule 
it concerns whether any single member of nato or the warsaw pact 
should be allowed to hold more than 30 percent of permitted 
weapons as the bush administration proposes or be allowed up to 
40 percent as moscow favors 
evidently baker and shevardnadze struck a compromise on that 
question asked if they had agreed on 30 percent or 40 percent 
baker said its neither one of these 
we had a very productive discussion shevardnadze said i 
would like to note quite substantial progress and a better 
understanding we have made real headway 
earlier baker said the two sides still anticipate having a 
conventional forces treaty essentially agreed to in november or 
we will be unable to have a summit 
still unresolved are verification procedures for determining 
whether provisions of the treaty are being observed 
also unsettled is a separate proposed ussoviet treaty to 
reduce longrange nuclear missiles bombers and submarines by about 
30 percent bush hopes to sign that accord in moscow in december 
bush is expected to see shevardnadze when the president comes to 
new york this weekend to address the special general assembly 
session monday 
