<TEXT>
the senate ethics committee is at a turning 
point in its investigation of five senators who tried to help 
former savings and loan operator charles h keating jr when his 
institution was heading toward collapse 
committee members have been meeting over the last two weeks to 
decide whether the cases of some or all the senators should be 
either dismissed or expanded 
keatings lincoln savings and loan association in irvine 
calif was taken over by the government in april 1989 and it 
could cost taxpayers more than 2 billion to cover the thrifts 
losses 
keating and his associates contributed some 13 million to the 
campaigns and causes of the five senators republican john mccain 
of arizona and democrats alan cranston of california dennis 
deconcini of arizona john glenn of ohio and donald w riegle jr 
of michigan 
all have said their intervention was routine assistance for 
someone who complained of unfair treatment by regulators 
the committee meetings could end a preliminary inquiry any 
cases kept alive could bring those senators long ethics hearings 
structured like a trial 
the preliminary phase was announced by the sixmember committee 
last dec 22 and a few senators have grumbled that ethics 
investigations take too long 
in response sen jesse helms rnc a member of the committee 
of three democrats and three republicans said the senators on the 
panel wish it could be expedited 
asked if the long investigation was unfair to the senators known 
as the keating five helms replied how do you define 
unfairness do you suggest we dont work every angle we just have 
a heavy load 
the case is proving difficult because no specific senate rule 
provides guidelines on what constitutes undue influence by a member 
of congress who intervenes with regulators in this case all five 
senators met with regulators on keatings behalf 
the ethics committee must determine if the senators actions in 
the keating case violated a resolution prohibiting improper 
conduct which may reflect upon the senate 
the senators intervened with us banking regulators in april 
1987 on behalf of keating 
edwin j gray then chairman of the federal home loan bank 
board said the four senators with whom he met in the first of two 
meetings backed a deal to aid keatings future operations the 
senators all except riegle who did not attend vigorously 
denied that any deal was proposed 
at a second meeting with the regulators in charge of the lincoln 
examination all five senators were told that matters in the case 
would be referred to the justice department for a criminal 
investigation 
keating this month was indicted in california on state criminal 
fraud charges 
congressional sources said that lacking a specific rule on 
senators conduct with executive branch officials the ethics panel 
could seek guidance from the recent cases of former house speaker 
jim wright dtexas and sen dave durenberger rminn 
wright resigned from congress more than a year ago after the 
house ethics committee filed formal charges against him 
durenberger was denounced by the senate in july for violating 
senate rules on receipt of gifts speaking fee limits financial 
disclosure and campaign contributions 
in durenbergers case one key issue was not covered by a 
specific rule 
the ethics committee found that durenberger acted deceptively to 
hide his ownership in a minneapolis condominium from the senate so 
he could receive rent reimbursements to which he was not entitled 
the committee said the senator abused his office and misused 
funds through a pattern of improper conduct that has brought 
discredit upon the united states senate 
wright like the senators in the keating inquiry had intervened 
with the federal home loan bank board in the speakers case he 
did so on behalf of texans who complained of unfair treatment 
while the house ethics committee eventually found little 
evidence of undue influence by wright the special counsel in the 
case wrote of the principles governing proper and improper 
intervention 
the counsel richard phelan said a house advisory opinion 
considered it proper for a member to request information or a 
status report from regulators to urge prompt consideration of a 
matter arrange for interviews or appointments express judgments 
and call for reconsideration of a decision 
but phelan said a member should treat all constituents equally 
and there should be no direct or implied suggestion of favoritism 
or reprisal involving the agency 
