uranium miners and western residents who lost 
their health from exposure to nuclear weapons tests would get a 
formal apology and compensation under legislation headed to 
president bushs desk 
the house on thursday approved a bill that authorizes 100 
million for a radiation exposure trust fund to pay people who 
developed cancer from either mining uranium or because they lived 
downwind of the nevada test site for the atomic bomb 
the senate passed the bill previously 
we are here saying that as a nation in the dangerous and 
difficult postwar period we were confronted with a brand new 
technology said rep barney frank dmass who led debate on 
the bill before the voice vote feeling very much threatened and 
needing that technology for our defense we acted hastily 
he said residents in the test area were exposed to levels of 
radiation we would not allow now miners were sent into the mines 
without even the slightest protection against the material they 
were being asked to mine 
frank said the bill is an acknowledgement that the government 
was wrong 
people with cancer who lived in nevada arizona or utah downwind 
from nuclear testing between 1951 and 1958 or between june and 
july 1962 would be eligible for compensation under the 
legislation 
uranium miners in colorado new mexico arizona wyoming and 
utah from 1947 to 1971 who got cancer also would be eligible 
it would be up to the justice department to determine the amount 
of compensation for each person and process claims 
a driving force behind the legislation was stewart udall a 
former congressman and interior secretary whose brother rep 
morris udall dariz is chairman of the house interior committee 
he represented the uranium miners in a lawsuit against the 
federal government the courts ruled the government was immune from 
prosecution because national security dictated a need for the 
