<TEXT>
alaska stands to reap a windfall of 
millions of dollars in oil revenue thanks to the persian gulf 
crisis and gov steve cowper wants to sock most of it away for a 
rainy day 
cowper and many lawmakers argue that a fund is needed to ease an 
expected drop in oil revenues later this decade as alaska oil 
production declines oil gas taxes and royalties account for about 
85 percent of state revenues 
the governor said thursday if oil prices dont collapse before 
the end of the year the state will have a substantial surplus 
the increase in state revenues since iraq invaded kuwait aug 2 
already has erased the projected deficit that prompted cowper in 
july to veto 325 million from the 29 billion fiscal 1991 budget 
each 1 rise in the price of one barrel of oil adds 150 million 
to alaskas treasury over a year this years budget was based on 
oil selling at 1933 prices this week have been double that 
cowper who declined to seek a second term and leaves office 
dec 3 said he will propose that the 1991 legislature restore some 
budget cuts when it convenes in late january but place most of the 
windfall in a budget reserve 
voters will decide nov 6 whether to amend the state 
constitution to create a reserve fund 
its prudent to do because oil prices can go down as quickly 
as they went up cowper said 
also the huge prudhoe bay oil field the nations largest is 
in decline when it dries up so will alaskas free ride on oil 
the state has no state sales or income taxes 
its uncertain how next years new legislature will react to the 
windfall 
some lawmakers likely will push to deposit the cash in the 
alaska permanent fund an 112 billion state savings account 
funded with a fixed percentage of the states oil and mineral 
revenues since 1977 
but tapping that fund for future government expenses may be 
difficult the funds principal by law cannot be spent and theres 
strong public and political opposition to spending the earnings for 
other uses it also would reduce the size of dividends each alaskan 
receives every year from the fund 
past legislatures spent oil surpluses on roads sewers power 
projects buildings and other publi works projects in the young 
and largely undeveloped state 
the rationale will be hey weve got the money lets sow 
the seeds for the future while we can said sen pat pourchot 
a democrat 
but rep ramona barnes a republican predicted there will also 
be strong public pressure to save the cash 
the public is not going to stand for the legislature to just 
spend that money willynilly on everything that comes by she 
said theyre going to expect that money to be saved for a rainy 
day 
