<TEXT>
leading japanese lawmakers and north koreas ruling 
party agreed today that the two countries should begin formal 
negotiations in november to establish diplomatic ties 
the joint declaration signed in pyongyang north koreas 
capital marked a sharp departure from the norths past policy of 
opposition to ties with countries that recognize rival south korea 
south koreas foreign ministry today reacted with caution to the 
news of improving relations between japan and north korea 
officials said they welcomed a liberalization of the norths 
isolationist policy but said japanese moves to strengthen ties 
should be made slowly and in consultation with south korea 
some observers have suggested north koreas move to establish 
relations with japan might have been triggered by south koreas 
steps toward ties with the soviet union a close ally of north 
korea 
normalization of ties by tokyo and pyongyang would end 45 years 
of estrangement between japan and north korea beginning at the end 
of world war ii when the peninsula was divided 
south korea normalized relations with japan in 1965 
the joint communique came at the end of five days of talks in 
north korea between the japanese lawmakers group and north korean 
officials including president kim il sung the talks were the 
highestlevel discussions ever by the two countries 
the japanese delegation made up of lawmakers from japans 
governing and largest opposition parties agreed that tokyo should 
pay compensation to north korea for its past colonial rule over the 
korean peninsula japanese and north korean news reports said 
although the discussions were between north korean and japanese 
political parties rather than their governments the communique is 
believed to represent a commitment by both sides 
the japanese group was headed by former deputy prime minister 
shin kanemaru a powerful leader of the governing liberal 
democratic party and by japan socialist party vice chairman makoto 
tanabe 
the socialists have served as a bridge between the two nations 
in the absence of formal diplomatic relations 
during the talks kim agreed to release two japanese seamen 
detained since 1983 on espionage charges removing a key impediment 
to relations north korean officials said thursday the two men will 
be freed in october japans kyodo news service reported 
todays declaration said the two countries should quickly 
establish satellite communications links and direct air flights to 
help improve relations the two countries now have no direct 
telephone mail or travel connections 
the joint declaration also called for an end to discrimination 
against koreans living in japan and for peaceful unification of 
north and south korea through dialogue between the divided nations 
