the united states and 20 other industrialized 
nations laid plans today to try to protect the west from a 
potential oil supply crisis but said there was no immediate need to 
tap strategic reserves to offset the loss of oil from iraq and 
kuwait 
the international energy agency said that eight weeks after 
iraqs invasion of kuwait oil markets remain adequately supplied 
and no product shortages have materialized in member countries 
after a closeddoor meeting governing board members of the 
agency urged in a communique that member countries intensify energy 
conservation and efficiency measures 
they also urged governments to allow the full increase in oil 
prices to pass through to the market and suggested flexibility 
in the area of environmental regulations 
the communique called on all member countries to take all 
decisions necessary in order to be able to act immediately and 
effectively if need be 
if a significant shortfall of oil supplies develops the board 
will convene an emergency session it said the governing board 
will reconvene sometime during october regardless of whether an 
emergency becomes necessary 
oil companies were advised to continue drawing on commercial 
stocks and to use discretion in purchases to minimize volatility in 
the world oil market 
echoing the conclusion of the boards aug 31 meeting the 
communique said recent oil price rises were driven by extreme 
political uncertainty not by actual shortages 
