raul manglapus has said the country wants an immediate us pullout 
from clark air base when the current lease expires nxt september 
the shortterm misbenefit to filipinos for an immediate cutoff 
would be tremendous estanislao said in answer to a question at a 
news conference 
estanislao said the talks are covering a wide range of 
usphilippine issues including the possibility of debt reduction 
in place of some direct payment if us use of the facilities is 
continued 
he said assessments have been made of the impact of a loss of 
the bases but he declined to give figures he said the figures 
were not very precise but the country has contingency plans for the 
bases 
internationalism has advantages and isolation has its costs 
estanislao said 
members of the us congress familiar with the negotiations have 
said they expect the united states to seek agreement to rent some 
key facilities if a phaseout is necessary 
estanislao said it is important that the talks conclude 
successfully because it would be a very bad signal to investors 
if they end with acrimony between the two sides 
the financial secretary said increasing oil prices have not yet 
been fully felt in manila because the country is still running on 
oil purchased prior to iraqs aug 2 takeover of kuwait 
but he said the need for additional funds because of the crisis 
is expected to be between 1 billion and 2 billion depending on 
the price of oil 
the challenges for us seem to get bigger by the day no thanks 
to saddam hussein he said referring to the leader of iraq the 
country also has suffered a major earthquake drought and massive 
flooding in recent weeks 
the philippines also is hit by the loss of foreign exchange from 
thousands of filipino workers in iraq and kuwait and the need to 
give them jobs when they return 
estanislao said major economic goals for the country include 
giving more assistance to small and mediumsized businesses rather 
than larger privilegeseeking industries and narrowing the gap 
between the 68 percent interest paid to savers and the 2230 
percent charged to borrowers in by philippine banks 
before the gulf crisis and recent calamities the economy was 
growing at an annual rate of 6 percent and inflations was below 10 
percent a year estanislao said 
he said the country is getting from 25 billion to 3 billion 
under a multilateral assistance program for 1990 and expects an 
increase in 1991 but officials said the money needed as a result 
of the gulf crisis is in addition to those funds which are for 
economic development 
