<TEXT>
the texas system of electing district judges 
at large was upheld today by the 5th us circuit court of appeals 
which ruled that judicial elections do not fall under the voting 
rights act 
the ruling rejected arguments by minorities who said that such 
atlarge voting denies them an equal chance to elect candidates 
they want by in effect diluting their votes among a large 
population of voters 
the ruling applied specifically to nine urban counties in texas 
but was eagerly awaited because of possible broader application in 
louisiana a similar challenge to judicial districting is pending 
with a court hearing scheduled this afternoon a challenge is also 
pending in georgia which is in a different circuit of the appeals 
court 
a threejudge panel of the appeals court had upheld the atlarge 
voting system in a 21 ruling in may but brought the case back 
before the entire 15member court for reconsideration 
the majority opinion written by thomas gibbs gee of houston 
said the judge are not representatives of the people 
these offices are not representative ones and their 
occupants are not representatives he said indeed the state 
processes for filling them need not even be elective as those for 
all representative offices presumably must be 
sam d johnson of austin in a scathing dissent called the 
decision a burning scar on the flesh of the voting rights act 
the majority opinion is not simply wrong it is dangerous 
no previous court has ever even suggested that judicial 
elections might be exempt from the reach of section 2 of the the 
voting rights act he wrote 
in the majority opinion gee wrote that in 1982 congress passed 
a law to test for dilution of voting strength but stopped short of 
imposing such a test for judicial offices 
should congress seek to install such a test for judicial 
elections it must say so plainly the court said 
instead it has thus far plainly said the contrary 
the case was brought to court by the league of united latin 
american citizens and other miniority groups who said atlarge 
voting for state judges prevents them from electing minority 
candidates 
us district judge lucius bunton of midland agreed ruling that 
the system violated the voting rights act he ordered the state to 
divide the nine counties into electoral subdistricts 
those counties dallas harris bexar tarrant travis 
lubbock midland ector and jefferson elect 172 of texas 390 
district judges who rule on matters of state law and preside over 
trials 
the threejudge panel of the appeals court reversed buntons 
decision saying that congress did not mean for judicial elections 
to fall under the voting rights act 
in the louisiana district judge case us district judge john 
parker ordered that 11 districts be redesigned to enhance the 
chance of electing black judges 
only six of louisianas 254 district and appellate court judges 
are black 
also at issue in louisiana is a state supreme court district in 
new orleans the only district in the state represented by two 
justices elected at large 
</TEXT>
