<TEXT>
after 83 years the final stone will be placed 
atop washington cathedrals st paul tower on saturday fulfilling 
pierre lenfants vision of a great church for national 
purposes 
president bush will be on hand just as president theodore 
roosevelt was when a foundation stone quarried in bethlehem was 
laid at noon sept 29 1907 
the church is the seat of the bishop of the episcopal diocese of 
washington but also calls itself a place of prayer for all 
people and has often held interdenominational services bush is 
an episcopalian 
the final stone a 1000pound chunk of indiana limestone carved 
in the shape of a folded leaf will be lifted to its perch on the 
cathedrals southwest pinnacle 234 feet above the ground by a 
giant crane 
partly sunny and warm weather is predicted jean grigsby a 
spokeswoman for the cathedral said at least 10000 people were 
expected about as many as attended the 1907 ceremony 
lenfant the frenchborn architect and engineer hired by george 
washington to lay out the nations capital included a nationl 
church in his plan that plan was never fully realized 
the 873021square foot building roughly 14th century english 
gothic in style is the sixth largest cathedral in the world 
st peters in rome is the largest followed by one in seville 
the unfinished st john the divine in new york and cathedrals in 
liverpool and milan 
although it is known as washington national cathedral the 
official name of the building is the cathedral church of st peter 
and st paul 
constructionbegan at the east end with the laying of the 
foundation stone in what is now bethlehem chapel the twin towers 
at the west end a tenth of a mile away are named for sts peter 
and paul 
work on the cathedral was halted during world war i and world 
war ii and stopped again in 1977 because of a shortage of funds it 
was resumed in 1980 
president dwight d eisenhowers funeral was held in the 
cathedral president woodrow wilson is buried there seven bishops 
have presided over it the rev martin luther king jr and the rev 
desmond tutu have spoken from its pulpit 
the 150000ton church was built in the traditional 
stoneonstone method of the medieval cathedral builders although 
with modern equipment it has no steel reinforcement but is 
supported by flying buttresses 
it is set on 53 acres on mount st alban the highest point in 
washington 
saturdays ceremony will be followed by a service of 
consecration sunday 
provost charles a perry who played a key role in the 
completion of the cathedral will deliver his final sermon at the 
consecration he is moving on to become president of the episcopal 
church divinity school of the pacific in berkeley calif 
as chief administrator of the cathedral perry argued at a 
crucial point in 1983 that by building on a payasyou go basis 
the cathedral could both complete its west towers and expand its 
program of outreach to the poor 
bishop john t walker who inaugurated the final phase of 
construction in 1980 shortly after becoming bishop died after 
heart surgery on sept 30 1989 the day of a service marking the 
beginning of the final year of construction he is buried in the 
cathedral crypt 
his successor bishop john t haines will be installed nov 15 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

