<TEXT>
sixteen military units will be 
disbanded and two air bases closed in troop cutbacks prompted by 
lessening tensions and escalating economic woes in south africa 
officials said friday 
president fw de klerk has said defense forces can be reduced 
because of declining regional tensions partly linked to the 
governments plan to end apartheid 
meanwhile rising prices and a spreading recession has pressured 
officials to cut military spending yet still leaving south africa 
with the regions most powerful armed forces earlier this year 
the navy was cut by 25 percent 
gen jannie geldenhuys head of the armed services said 11 air 
force units and five army units would be disbanded or consolidated 
two air bases will be closed he said 
the defense ministry did not say how many troops would be 
involved in the cuts or how many would leave the military 
south africa has about 95000 troops about twothirds of whom 
are conscripts 
spending cuts will also mean reductions in training and 
exercises and withdrawal of some weapons and other equipment the 
officials said 
geldenhuys said the air forcess buccaneer jet bombers and 
cessna light trainer aircraft would be withdrawn from service 
radar coverage will also be reduced he said 
the cuts will not reduce the militarys offensive capability 
officials said neighboring nations have much smaller and weaker 
defense forces according to military analysts 
defense ministry officials declined to confirm a report friday 
in business day newspaper that defense spending would be cut by at 
least 5 percent or about 200 million 
government officials said the staterun armscor weapons company 
would also be hit by the spending cuts new projects would be 
halted or reduced and workers will be laid off 
armscor has dismissed about 2000 workers this year the company 
now employs about 20000 people 
armscor was set up by the government to produce weapons and 
munitions after the united nations imposed an embargo on south 
africa to protest the whiterun governments apartheid policies 
the company produces everything from tanks and artillery to 
ammunition and has become a major arms exporter 
