<TEXT>
a dispute friday about how to combat urban 
smog exposed the deep divisions that remain between house and 
senate negotiators as they try to craft a compromise clean air bill 
in the final weeks of the legislative session 
we have consumed nearly two weeks without making any 
progress said sen max baucus dmont chairman of the 
housesenate conference we are still miles apart on some 
issues 
during a meeting that some called critical to getting a 
clean air bill completed before congress adjourns next month the 
senate flatly rejected a house proposal for pollution controls on 
automobiles and accused the house of stalling because it had taken 
11 days to prepare 
the negotiations which began july 13 has focused in recent 
weeks on what pollution controls to impose on automobiles and 
requirements for a limited phasein of alternative fuel vehicles 
the issue has been of major importance to rep john dingell 
dmich chairman of the house delegation dingells state is home 
to the major us automakers 
senators had complained for days that the house wasnt 
responding to a proposal submitted in midseptember then when the 
house proposal was received the senate quickly rejected it as 
being so unacceptable that it cannot even serve as a basis of 
discussion 
dingell accused the senator of engaging in speechmaking instead 
of focusing on the issue 
i feel whats going on is a delay strategy said sen john 
chafee rri suggesting that staunch opponents of the clean air 
bill may succeed in blocking it in the final days of congress 
both the house and senate earlier this year overwhelmingly 
approved clean air bills that impose tough new pollution controls 
on utilities factories and automobiles but efforts to work out 
differences in the two bills have made only slow progress 
earlier this week president bush raised the possibility that 
the bill may die if the pace of negotiations isnt quickened 
fridays squabble centered on concerns from senate negotiators 
about provisions that would require tougher emission controls on 
automobiles and the phasein of alternative fuel vehicles to reduce 
urban smog 
