<TEXT>
a medicine trader who mistook a poisonous 
chemical for a cough syrup ingredient is to blame for the deaths of 
at least 109 children government officials said 
the case also illustrates the widespread problem of fake and 
dangerous drugs sold in this west african nation such durgs claim 
hundreds of lives annually authorities say 
investigators quoted in lagos newspapers saturday editions said 
the unidentified trader bought unlabeled drums believed to contain 
harmless glycol but which actually held ethylene glycol a 
poisonous chemical stolen from an oil companys warehouses 
ethylene glycol causes kidney failure 
the trader poured the chemical into smaller bottles labeled as 
propylene glycol used commonly in nigeria as a solvent for the 
preparation of cough syrup the bottles bore the name of a dutch 
company 
investigators were trying to determine whether the trader forged 
the labels or used old bottles the newspaper said 
the trader has been arrested but the person who sold him the 
ethylene glycol was still being sought friday 
forty percent to 50 percent of drugs available in nigeria are 
bogus or substandard said the united nations world health 
organization representative in nigeria sh brewergraves last 
april 
drugs are sold in licensed and unlicensed stores as well as by 
street hawkers and vendors in market places 
under laws passed last year those convicted of medicine fraud 
could face up to one year in prison and a maximum fine of about 
127 a large amount for most nigerians 
