<TEXT>
a federal jury on friday ordered a 
manufacturer of room partitions to pay 51 million in connection 
with a 1986 new years eve arson fire that killed 97 hotel guests 
the us district court jury found air wall inc guilty of nine 
counts of negligence and 10 counts of failure to warn users about 
possible hazards associated with its foamfilled dividers at the 
dupont plaza hotel 
it was not immediately clear what potential hazards were cited 
by the jury which decided the walls contributed to the fastmoving 
fire linked to a labor dispute in puerto ricos most populous city 
in a separate trial three former hotel employees were convicted 
of murder in 1987 for setting the fire to pressure management to 
give into union demands the union itself has denied any 
responsibility 
the fire broke out in a ballroom on the first floor of the 
22story hotel and most of the victims were trapped in the casino 
the beachside hotel which has still not reopened was filled with 
nearly 1000 guests at the time also 140 people were injured 
air wall was acquitted of 17 other counts including all 12 
counts of productive defectiveness 
five other companies that supplied rugs dressers and foam 
cushions used by the hotel were acquitted of all charges following 
seven days of jury deliberations to end the 15month trial 
defense attorney harold vicente said air wall would appeal to 
the first circuit of appeals in boston on grounds of confusion 
among the jurors 
if the product was not defective what did we have to warn 
about vicente said following the verdict 
it was second phase of one of the largest disasterrelated 
lawsuits in us history 
the first phase ended in may 1989 when judge raymond l acosta 
accepted a 100 million settlement of hundreds of individual 
lawsuits stemming from the dec 31 1986 
judge acosta now must decide whether to go ahead with the third 
phase of the trial which entails suits and countersuits filed by 
some of the firms and insurers or proceed to the remaining 264 
individual suits 
fridays verdict stemmed from 12 lawsuits filed against hotel 
suppliers by survivors and relatives of people killed in the fire 
wyomingbased air wall manufactured portable styrofoamfilled 
partitions used on the floor of the hotel ballroom 
the jury determined the four companies that have owned air wall 
at various times since 1962 must share in paying damages they are 
white consolidated industries inc aircoustic wall manufacturing 
co acw airwall inc and hufcor inc 
hector martinez a lawyer for the four firms said the appeal 
would be based on jurors confusion caused by the complicated 
nature of the case and the voluminous trial documentation he said 
there were about 15000 pages of testimony alone 
i think i have a very good argument for appeal and i am very 
pleased with the result vicente agreed 
he explained that he had expected a much higher damage award 
originally the suits filed against his clients totaled 25 
million 
lawyers for the plaintiffs also said they were satisfied with 
the jury award 
attorney francisco troncoso said the award breaks ground for 
settlements in the individual cases are tried 
companies cleared by the jury of liability were drexel heritage 
furnishings industries of north carolina dan river inc of 
virginia lewis industries inc of california foss manufacturing 
company inc of massaschussetts and wolf gordon inc of new york 
drexel heritage was the supplier of dressers that were stored in 
the ballroom at the time of the fire dan river wolf gordo and 
foss supplied rugs used on the walls and floor of the ballroom and 
lewis industries was the manufacturer of the foam used to fill sofa 
cushions stored in the ballroom 
the fourth and final phase of the litigation concerns suits 
filed by the owners of the hotel against the teamsters union 
