the oregon supreme court on friday restored 
five voter initiative measures to the nov 6 ballot reversing a 
ruling that had disqualified them on a technicality 
the state high court announced its unanimous decision after 
hearing arguments on the appeal the court had no further comment 
saying written opinions would be issued at a later date 
one of the five issues put back on the ballot would allow tax 
credits for partent who sent their children to parochial schools 
marion county circuit judge richard barber ruled monday that the 
five initiatives were not eligible for the ballot because they 
lacked financial statements the statements werent included 
because of an earlier court rulings saying state officials missed a 
deadline for formally approving them 
state law requires that financial estimates be printed on 
ballots and in the state voters pamphlet for measures having a 
substantial impact on the state treasury 
other measures affected by the high court ruling would limit 
property taxes shut down the trojan nuclear plant until waste 
disposal requirements are met ban some nonrecyclable packaging 
and set up a pilot work program for welfare applicants 
in a secondary ruling the supreme court upheld the earlier 
court decisions that had struck financial impact statements from 
three measures on grounds officials missed a deadline for approving 
them 
