publics initiative rights shouldnt be breached because of 
procedural mistakes by the government 
mike reynolds an assistant attorney general said the fiscal 
statement law is ambiguous and should be construed so as not to 
abort the right of initiative 
but robert durham a lawyer for foes of the tax measures said 
voters have a material right to have financial statements the 
measures his clients oppose have potentially catastrophic 
multibillion dollar impacts he said 
elections officials have said the fiscal statements might be 
posted in voting booths as a substitute for having them on the 
ballot or in the voters pamphlet 
