<DOCNO> AP900928-0173 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the texas system of electing district judges 
by countywide voting was upheld friday by a federal appeals court 
that said questions about possibly diluted minority voting strength 
do not apply 
protections against diluting the voting power of minorities have 
no bearing on the election of judges because they are not public 
servants the 5th us circuit court of appeals ruled 121 
judge sam d johnson of austin texas in a scathing 47page 
dissent wrote the majority opinion is not simply wrong it is 
dangerous 
the decision affects nine texas counties but has possible 
broader applications it came hours before a similar challenge was 
to be argued in a baton rouge federal court 
another challenge is pending in georgia which is in a different 
federal appeals court circuit 
the majority opinion written by judge thomas gibbs gee of 
houston said judges unlike legislators and other elected 
officials are not public servants in fact they often must defy 
public opinion to carry out the law he wrote 
gee wrote that section 2 of the voting rights act an amendment 
passed in 1982 was a test to determine what dilutes voting 
strength but it stopped short of imposing such a test for judicial 
offices 
should congress seek to install such a test for judicial 
elections it must say so plainly he wrote instead it has 
thus far plainly said the contrary 
in his dissent johnson called the majority decision completely 
isolated from other rulings 
no previous court has ever even suggested that judicial 
elections might be exempt from the reach of section 2 of the voting 
rights act he wrote to the contrary this court had 
earlier concluded that section 2 applied to all elections 
including judicial elections 
not only does the majority opinion reverse this twoyearold 
precedent but it also demonstrates a shocking lack of concern for 
the urgently argued position of the attorney general who has 
consistently maintained that the voting rights act reaches all 
elections 
the case was brought to court by the league of united latin 
american citizens which argued that countywide voting for state 
judges in nine urban counties prevents minorities from electing the 
candidates they want 
us district judge lucius bunton of midland agreed and ordered 
the state to divide the nine counties into electoral subdistricts 
those counties dallas harris bexar tarrant travis 
lubbock midland ector and jefferson elect 172 of texas 390 
district judges 
a threejudge panel of the 5th circuit upheld the texas system 
however it then brought the case back before the entire panel for 
reconsideration thirteen of the 15 circuit court members 
participated 
an attorney for the group said theyll appeal to the supreme 
court 
we think that any election system that discriminates on the 
basis of race and ethnicity is inconsistent with the most basic 
democratic principles of our society said rolando rios of san 
antonio 
the texas and louisiana cases are virtually identical 
were just delighted with the opinion said john kennedy 
legal counsel for louisiana gov buddy roemer its a complete 
victory 
in the louisiana case us district judge john parker ordered 
that 11 districts be redesigned to enhance the chance of electing 
black judges only six of louisianas 254 district and appellate 
court judges are black 
also at issue in louisiana is a state supreme court district in 
new orleans the only district in the state represented by two 
justices elected at large 
a similar challenge in mississippi led to special judicial 
elections being held in 1989 under a federal court order 
us district judge william h barbour jr of jackson was the 
first federal judge in the nation to apply section 2 of the voting 
rights act to judicial elections his ruling which said the 
states judicial districts discriminated against blacks was upheld 
by a special threejudge federal panel appointed to review the 
decision 
