<TEXT>
does it make sense to penalize the middle class 
in order to deny the wealthy 
elected officials argued in recent weeks that to accede to 
president bushs wish and lower the maximum capital gains tax to 15 
percent from 28 percent would disproportionately benefit the rich 
that would never do they said 
what many opponents failed to explain is that a lower tax also 
would benefit the hardworking middle class including many 
farmers owners of small businesses small investors and various 
other lessthanrich americans 
it would help farmers who built up a valuable property from 
nothing and who now wish to retire homeowners whose financial 
gains on a property sale exceed the deductible limit entrepreneurs 
who created value out of an idea 
the big investor would benefit from lower taxes but so would 
the investor who put 3000 into stocks in 1985 saw them grow 
to 3500 in 1990 and who after taxes commissions and inflation 
has about a 180 profit 
had that person put the money in a relatively riskless savings 
account earning just over 5 percent annually the aftertax 
afterinflation profit might have been more than double that 
this is but one example of inconsistencies in the capital gains 
debate during which the issue became so embroiled in politics that 
several of the important financial and social implications were 
lost 
it takes capital investments for example to develop new 
businesses which create wealth provide jobs and eventually grow 
large enough to compete with larger companies thus adding to 
market competition and fair pricing 
it takes people with ideas too and often those people do not 
have the capital unlike existing businesses that have ready access 
to capital from pension funds the beginners must beg for capital 
and they must offer something in return 
what they offer investors is a reasonable hope that the company 
will succeed and repay them for accepting the risk and the 
longterm commitment of their funds 
in the capital gains debate profit was mentioned far more than 
risk but profit is never assured in capital investments whereas 
risk is risk means the possibility of loss and that possibility 
is high small companies often fail 
there has to be a good inducement therefore for investors to 
commit money to risky but economically and socially worthwhile 
ventures but taxes and longterm inflation beginners will tell 
you sometimes destroy that inducement 
throughout the debate references were made to the taxdeferred 
aspect of capital investments but less was said about the 
longterm commitment of those funds which of course precludes 
their use in any other way 
that issue might seem minor but that commitment of funds can be 
for a lifetime during which the investor might build a large 
operation but have a relatively small income his wealth is 
committed it cannot be withdrawn 
perhaps the most positive result of the debate was to clarify 
the meaning of profit if profit really was what it was defined as 
being by otherwise informed people then everyone would be rich 
inflation they said was profit 
on reflection everyone understands that inflation is a minus 
it is deducted from profit ten percent inflation wipes out a 5 
percent wage increase and leaves you with a 5 percent loss not a 
profit 
somehow that reasoning was not always applied to capital gains 
where inflation was called profit even by political leaders who 
claimed to have thoroughly analyzed the issue in fact inflation 
was actually taxed as profit 
that irony at least has been clarified 
