elections for the nations 435 house seats are 
likely to yield only slight shifts in power but analysts caution 
that this years voting could be among the most volatile and 
unpredictable in years 
novembers balloting will follow one of the strangest 18 
months in recent political history analyst charles cook says of 
a period that has seen upheavals in eastern europe the persian 
gulf domestic issues and the american economy 
few are willing to bet on where it all will lead but most 
analysts and operatives are guessing that democrats will pad their 
258to176 majority by less than 10 seats 
in normal times that would be a facesaving outcome for 
republicans as the party in control of the white house the gop 
historically could expect to lose 15 or more house seats in an 
offyear election 
several factors would seem to favor the gop this time around 
president bush enjoys nearrecord popularity ratings his standing 
increased by his handling of the middle east crisis and polls show 
a general public disgust with congress which is controlled by the 
democrats 
but on the other side of the ledger the economy among the 
most powerful determinants of political fortune is headed 
downward and republicans are being forced to defend more socalled 
open seats where there is no incumbent seeking reelection 
because 11 otherwise safe gop house members are running for the 
senate or state offices 
the effect of the volatility has been to put most races into 
slow motion congress which had planned to adjourn by oct 5 so 
members could go home and campaign now is unlikely to get out of 
washington until oct 20 or so 
issues that have taken on local importance from abortion to 
taxes and the savings and loan crisis have had to compete for air 
time and headlines with developments in iraq and kuwait political 
experts say the effect will be to compress the intense part of the 
election season into the final two weeks 
for one in five house districts that will make no difference 
seventysix incumbent lawmakers 42 democrats and 34 republicans 
will coast to reelection without major party opposition 
and as has become common in house contests few of their 
