<TEXT>
from mexico to chile millions of latin 
american indians descendants of warriors who fought the spanish 
conquerors five centuries ago are again rising against the white 
man 
the new fighting spirit was sparked by official plans to 
celebrate in 1992 the 500th year of the discovery of america by 
spain but the real goals are better living conditions and equal 
rights to land schools health care and jobs 
a survey by associated press correspondents shows the regions 
30 million indians are by far the poorest segment of latin 
americas 437 million residents 
various reports from un agencies governments and private 
groups had come to the same conclusion based on indians poor 
general living conditions generally inadequate housing lack of 
frequent access to utilities and even more limited access if any 
to education 
most nonindian latin americans view the discovery celebrations 
as a tribute to the merging of the european and indian culture and 
to the spanish legacy 
for the indians it is a sour reminder of what they see as 
bloody conquest and material and cultural spoliation 
the spanish conquerors transferred tons of gold and silver to 
spain from the newly discovered land especially from mexico and 
peru after dominating the natives in bloody wars 
the spanish conquest must be repudiated celebrating it would 
shameful and the justification of a massacre said manuel castro 
an indian leader in ecuador 
nearly everywhere in latin america indian organizations are 
protesting the plans for solemnly marking the centennial which 
includes a visit to the region in october by the spanish king and 
queen 
many are seeking elimination of columbus day oct 12 as a 
holiday they demand it be declared a day of indian dignity 
genaro dominguez leader of the regional coordinating agency of 
nndian peoples in mexico central america and the caribbean said 
that instead of marking oct 12 with a tribute to columbus indians 
in his region are paying homage to mexicos indian leader 
cuahutemoc 
but the new fight centers most on demands for progress on 
indians social and economic problems 
about 300 delegates from 120 indian groups gathered last july in 
quito ecuador and passed a resolution vowing to fight for 
autonomy saying the centennial opens a new stage in the struggle 
of our peoples 
indians in latin america seldom have access to their nations 
job market 
those who emigrate to the cities often end up getting low menial 
jobs though there have been reports of indian professional success 
stories recently in guatemala and most complain of what they call 
discrimination from the white man 
others remaining in wartorn countryside such as el salvador and 
peru live in shacks in reducciones small plots of generally 
poor land remnants of the sprawling territories their ancestors 
once owned most reducciones lack basic services such as 
electricity and running water 
besides urban emigration worsens racism and discrimination 
said marcelino cayuqueo an araucano indian leader in argentina 
in addition to facing widespread prejudices such as the 
belief that all indians are lazy dirty and drink too much said 
chilean mapuche indian leader jose ancan many of them develop what 
sociologists call the indian syndrome 
cayuqueo described the syndrome as an instinctive rejection by 
indians to accept their condition as such 
thats a common problem among mexicos 15 million indians 
nearly onefourth of the mexican population those who emigrate to 
the cities usually only get modest jobs such as domestic work or 
end up begging in the streets 
arturo warman an executive of mexicos institute of indian 
studies said there are about 5 million indians living under 
extreme poverty in that country illiteracy is rampant about 
350000 indians in honduras are reported plagued by poverty and 
disease living in hamlets in remote mountain areas 
meliton garcia a mexican indian leader said the proper way to 
mark the centennial would be by solving our problems 
indian leaders say the solution to their problems must begin 
with the recognition by the governments of their ethnic traditions 
cultures language and religions and the restoration of their 
land 
last month 800 bolivian indians walked through the jungle 
lowlands from amazonia to the mountain city of la paz to demand 
land from the government president jaime paz zamora promised to 
meet their demands 
in bolivia where indians or dominantly indian mixedrace people 
account for about 80 percent of a population of 69 million they 
complain of discrimination from the white minority 
most indian leaders complain they also lack legislation to 
protect them or if it exists it doesnt work 
the laws are good in theory but they are not implemented or 
simply there is no money said julio estrada secretary of the 
colombian national organization 
in ecuador indians account for 35 percent of the andean 
nations 10 million people last august they showed their strength 
by staging two uprisings for three days they seized a number 
of highways and farms to press the government for solutions to 
their problems 
indians angrily dispute the notion of discovery of their land by 
the spaniards saying you dont discover a land that is already 
populated 
they also reject the roman catholic church joining the 
celebrations to mark the evangelization on the new world 
they imposed their god on people who already had their god or 
gods said mapuche leader ancan 
added juan carlos ramirez executive director of costa ricas 
national commission of indian affairs the celebrations have been 
poorly conceived the notion of discovery is diminishing to indian 
peoples 
political groups especially from the left and some missionary 
organizations have gained influence over the indian movement 
the mexicobased council for the restoration of indian rights 
admitted that the combative opposition to the centennial 
celebrations has political connotations 
one of the most widespread and controversial indian demands is 
the restoration of part of their ancestors land they claim was 
illegally taken from them by force by white farmers 
we want restoration of our land now said numa mallorquiin 
an indian leader in paraguay 
indians also claim they will not be fully integrated to the 
societies in their country unless the governments officially 
implement bilingual education in the schools 
war is long gone but violence is often still part of life for 
indians including a handful of tribes still living in primitive 
isolation 
in brazil where conquerors came from portugal not spain the 
