<TEXT>
has chase manhattan bank become the trendsetter 
among banks when it comes to slashing dividends 
that question has had the industry abuzz ever since chase sliced 
its payout to shareholders in half little more than a week ago 
regionals midlantic corp and southeast banking corp shortly 
thereafter said that they would cut or eliminate their dividends 
followed by similar announcement from the bigger bank of boston 
were still in a very awkward phase here said merrill lynch 
amp co analyst judah kraushaar many banks are reluctant to 
compare themselves with chase 
still experts agree that chases move takes the edge off other 
institutions which now feel they can trim dividends without a 
major public relations disaster 
high dividend yields which have been approaching 20 percent of 
earnings for some big banks have helped lure investors and prop 
up the price of bank stocks for some time but it seems that 
support is weakening 
bank stock prices have gone into a tailspin among issues that 
touched lows for the past year are bank of new york bankers trust 
jp morgan manufacturers hanover ncnb corp and first chicago 
among others 
citicorp for example traded as high as 3550 a share in the 
past 52 weeks but has sunk to around 14 its 178 dividend 
represents nearly 8 percent of the current stock price 
many people got used to idea that bank dividends are 
sacrosanct but given the way stock prices are being pounded there 
is a growing expectation within the institutional community that 
banks simply cannot sustain these dividends one industry 
observer said 
chase said halving its regular dividend to 120 per common 
share on an annual basis was part of its move to reach higher 
levels of capital analysts have estimated the move could save 
chase as much as 150 million a year 
saddled with nonperforming debt to third world countries and 
bad domestic real estate loans banks ability to increase earnings 
has been severely curtailed 
among institutions viewed as particularly vulnerable are the 
bank of new york chemical bank citibank and first chicago 
kraushaar said because their core capital or owners equity has 
declined below 4 percent 
the federal deposit insurance corp plans to approve a rule by 
the end of the year that would allow only the strongest banks 
about one in five to maintain a minimum core capital level of 3 
percent others would be required to maintain minimums ranging 
between 4 percent and 5 percent 
cutting or eliminating dividends would give banks a quick fix 
since money not paid out to investors could be poured back into 
earnings coffers but longterm problems still plague the industry 
a weakening economy a real estate market expected to get worse 
before it improves and a decline in general business activity 
from mergers and acquisitions to businesses capital spending plans 
will deprive banks of old revenue sources for some time to come 
one thing that would prop up bank stocks would be a lot of 
excess capacity coming out of the banking industry kraushaar 
said or in other words mergers between large institutions 
they could try to cut out lots of redundancies and build 
earnings through cost cutting he said 
the trick for investors is to identify the institutions that 
will survive 
