<TEXT>
midway airlines began cutting 500 people from its 
workforce today and blamed rising fuel costs as the cause 
chicagobased midway also said it would end service to savannah 
ga on nov 1 and reduce its service to 11 other cities beginning 
oct 15 
these actions are necessitated by escalating fuel costs 
brought on by the persian gulf crisis midway chairman david 
hinson said in a statement 
midway as well as other airlines is actively addressing the 
need to adjust system flying in order to reduce operating costs and 
produce a better balance between capacity and passenger demand 
hinson said 
the reduction will affect 10 percent of midways work force 
said spokeswoman sandra allen 
she said most of the 500 positions will be eliminated through 
layoffs that will be phased in through nov 1 some jobs will be 
eliminated by not filling positions vacated during the past several 
weeks allen said 
she said all departments in the company will be affected but 
declined to release specific numbers 
hinson said midway also plans to withdraw eight of its least 
fuel efficient aircraft from its fleet and replace them with more 
efficient md80 jetliners made by mcdonnell douglas corp 
he said midway took delivery of three md80s this month and 
expects to receive four more by year end 
midway airlines and midway commuter serve 59 cities in the 
united states canada the virgin islands and the bahamas 
the airline has major hubs in chicago and philadelphia 
</TEXT>
