<TEXT>
plans to rescue two united mine workers health 
care funds now staggering under an 88 million deficit are 
stirring anxiety among nonunion coal operators 
the operators fear a new industrywide coal tax will be proposed 
to bail out the troubled 1950 and 1974 umw health benefit trusts 
which serve 127052 retired union miners widows and dependents 
thats the big buzzword this week in the industry a growing 
feeling that nonunion companies may have to pay something 
said marc cohen coal analyst for kidder peabody amp co in new york 
in march us labor secretary elizabeth dole appointed an 
11member commission to study the trusts the panel which has no 
lawmaking power will release its recommendations at two meetings 
scheduled for oct 11 and oct 17 in washington 
henry perritt vice chairman of the commission said thursday 
theres been no decision on financing the trusts rescue but 
indicated some type of industrywide financing is being considered 
there is fairly strong evidence that the problem of health 
care obligation for retirees cant be solved in the long run 
without some kind of broadening of the financing obligations 
said perritt 
the panel also is looking at ways to improve the delivery of 
health care services to retirees said perritt 
my hope is well be able to put together a whole package to 
address the financing side and address the care delivery side that 
takes advantage of the thinking thats being expressed in the 
national dialogue on health care policy said perritt 
the panel will hold the last in a series of public hearings oct 
10 in washington where the coal tax issue is expected to dominate 
discussions 
mrs dole formed the commission on the heels of the umws 
10month strike against the pittston co the strike was triggered 
in part when the company stopped paying into the funds pittston 
said the payments hurt its competitiveness in the export market 
pittston settled with the union and contributed a 10 million 
lumpsum payment into the 1950 health fund 
the 1950 and 1974 funds are financed by coal companies that sign 
the national umw labor agreement known as the bituminous coal 
operators association contract 
but there are fewer bcoa companies to uupport the health plan 
than needed to keep it in the black about half of the industrys 
work force are union members 
now the 1950 fund faces a 73 million deficit while the 1974 
fund is 15 million in debt 
other problems include the high cost of health care and a 
federal lawsuit alleging mismanagement of the fund the funds are 
separate from the union and are operated by independent trustees 
the funds dilemma has delayed payments for health care services 
in the coalfields retirees and their families have problems 
finding drugstores that accept the umwa health plan card 
earlier this month eight nonunion coal companies protested the 
rumored bailout plan in a letter to labor secretary dole 
it would be an unprecedented projection of federal power into 
labor management relations in this country to require unionfree 
companies to pay for benefits available only to union members 
the letter said it was signed by officials for quaker coal co 
shell mining co mapco coal co addington resources coastal 
energy co arco coal co kerrmcgee coal corp and santa fe 
pacific coal corp 
forcing noninvolved companies to pick up the bill for 
parties failure to confront their economic problems in collective 
bargaining would establish an inappropriate and potentially 
catastrophic public policy the letter said 
one probable solution is transferring money from the unions fat 
pension fund to bail out the health trust last year the 1950 and 
1974 pension trusts showed 517 billion in assets after 
subtracting liabilities according to umw documents 
last year sen jay rockefeller dwva introduced a bill 
allowing transfer of money from the overfunded pension trusts to 
the ailing health care trusts the bill also would have required 
nonunion companies pay into the benefit trusts 
rockefellers bill has been placed on hold pending the 
commissions report provisions of the rockefeller bill including 
the pension fund transfer have been looked on favorably by the 
commission said two sources familiar with the study who requested 
anonymity 
</TEXT>
