<DOCNO> AP900928-0219 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after nearly four years of government and public 
scrutiny a shattered career and a humiliating guilty plea in wall 
streets worst scandal michael milken thought he had neared 
judgment day 
but milkens legal rite of reckoning in a manhattan federal 
courtroom on monday was postponed for reasons that could be either 
ominous or fortunate for the 44yearold prince of junkbond 
financing 
us district judge kimba m wood decided late last week to 
delay sentencing and hold an extraordinary hearing into numerous 
allegations of criminal conduct by milken that extend far beyond 
his six admitted felonies of conspiracy securities fraud mail 
fraud and aiding and abetting tax fraud 
she said the hearing likely to take place in midoctober would 
help her better understand whether milkens crimes were aberrant as 
the defense has claimed or systematic as alleged by the government 
wood is relatively new to the bench but widely acclaimed for 
careful handling of her first nationally prominent criminal 
sentencing faced with mountains of documents from both sides of 
the case painting widely divergent pictures of the accused she 
chose to solicit more information 
the hearing she has proposed presents formidable new hurdles for 
each side the government will have to lay out its evidence that 
milken was not only a crook but an unrepentant one milkens 
lawyers will be put in the uncomfortable position of deflecting 
those punches in a public forum which is something they had hoped 
to avoid 
the purpose is not to establish whether a defendant is guilty 
of every unadmitted defense that is precisely the opportunity the 
government chooses to forego when it accepts a guilty plea to fewer 
than all of the alleged crimes wood told the lawyers for both 
sides at a presentence hearing 
rather the purpose of considering unadmitted conduct is to 
give the court a sense of the defendants character as it is 
reflected in his conduct woods decision seemed to catch the 
prosecution and defense by surprise as it tossed them into vaguely 
charted legal waters it also left unresolved the final chapter of 
the tortuous milken story which began after ivan boesky pleaded 
guilty to securities fraud in november 1986 and put the government 
on the trail of the drexel burnham lambert junkbond wizard 
some lawyers even suggested the hearing raised the remote 
possibility that milken who tearfully pleaded guilty to the six 
counts in april after insisting he was innocent of any wrongdoing 
would scrap that deal and gamble anew on a fullblown jury trial 
obviously the hearing is going to complicate things said 
harry first a new york university law school expert on 
whitecollar crime i think this is fairly uncharted stuff 
others said it was the first time a judge in a whitecollar case 
had ordered what is known in legal circles as a fatico hearing it 
is named after carmine fatico a truck hijacker who was sentenced 
partly on the basis of a hearing into an uncharged crime his 
alleged membership in the mafia 
if the government wants the judge to consider something you 
werent convicted of the defense has a right to challenge it 
said lawyer thomas puccio a former assistant us attorney who 
prosecuted the fatico case thats what the hearing is for 
if wood were to conclude milken engaged in a pattern of 
cheating bribery insider trading and obstruction of justice from 
the junkbond trading desk at drexel as the prosecution alleged in 
its sentencing memorandum she would likely order a fairly harsh 
sentence 
on the other hand if she found him the benign generous 
philanthropist depicted by the defense shed be more inclined to 
give him a relatively mild punishment 
in any case wood cannot order milken imprisoned for more than 
the 28year maximum on the six counts in his plea many lawyers 
have said she might sentence him to far less even if she believed 
elements of the prosecutors portrayal because he has promised to 
cooperate in other probes 
milken is the biggest figure to fall in the securities fraud 
scandals of the 80s as measured by his prominence and the record 
600 million in fines and penalties he agreed to pay in his plea 
bargain 
by contrast boesky paid 100 million pleaded guilty to one 
count and received a threeyear term investment banker dennis b 
levine got two years imprisonment and a 362000 fine for insider 
trading mergers specialist martin a siegel received a twomonth 
prison term 3000 hours of community service and five years 
probation 
some legal experts interpreted woods decision to hold a special 
hearing as a sign that she found little to guide her toward a fair 
sentence from either the defense or the prosecution 
prosecutors implied milken should get at least six times the 
punishment of boesky since he paid six times the fine and admitted 
six times the crimes 
wood seemed to reject that implication at the presentencing 
hearing last week 
but she seemed no more persuaded by the defenses testimonials 
from people ranging from milkens childhood math teacher to the los 
angeles police chief beseeching her to view milken as a contrite 
firsttime offender who didnt care much about money and gave most 
of it away milkens defenders urged her to spare him from prison 
and let him work with innercity children 
what ultimately may arise from woods special hearing legal 
experts say is the first substantive look at the true strength of 
the governments case against milken had it gone to trial 
i applaud what she did said john coffee a columbia law 
school professor who has been following milkens case 
now were really going to get to that truthfinding function 
that the criminal justice system is designed for he said 
were going to have people tell us what happened 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
