<DOCNO> AP900928-0220 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here is a chronology of key developments in the prosecution of 
former drexel burnham lambert inc junkbond chief michael milken 
nov 14 1986 stock speculator ivan boesky pays 100 million 
to settle charges of insider trading on information supplied by 
investment banker dennis levine he agrees to cooperate with 
investigators and plead guilty to a single criminal charge boesky 
later is sentenced to three years in prison 
late 1986 published reports link milken to an illegal insider 
trading network led by boesky 
sept 7 1988 the securities and exchange commission accuses 
drexel milken and three others of violating a wide range of 
securities laws most in connection with boesky 
dec 21 drexel agrees to plead guilty to six felonies and pay 
a record 650 million in fines and restitution to settle the 
biggest securities fraud probe in history 
march 29 1989 a federal grand jury indicts milken brother 
lowell and former drexel trader bruce lee newberg on 98 counts of 
racketeering and fraud largely based on information supplied by 
boesky potential penalties and fines total 12 billion plus 
possible prison terms 
april 7 the milkens plead innocent newberg enters an innocent 
plea later 
april 13 drexel and the sec announce a settlement of the civil 
fraud case that subjects the firm to federal monitoring for three 
years and forces it to sever ties with milken 
june 15 milken resigns after 19 years at drexel to form his 
own consulting firm lowell milken quits to return to practicing 
law 
sept 11 drexel formally pleads guilty to six felonies and 
begins paying its fine 
feb 13 1990 drexels parent company files for federal 
bankruptcy court protection after defaulting on debts and begins 
laying off employees 
march 19 prosecutors promise to bring a new indictment with 
broader charges against milken by the week of april 16 
april 4 boesky is released from federal custody after 
completing two years of a threeyear term 
april 19 four months of negotiations intensify between the 
government and milken for a possible plea bargain to settle the 
case as a deadline looms for the new indictment 
april 24 milken pleads guilty to six felonies including 
conspiracy securities fraud mail fraud and assisting in the 
filing of a false tax return carrying a total maximum sentence of 
28 years imprisonment four of the counts directly involve boesky 
milken also agrees to pay 600 million in restitution and fines and 
cooperate with the government after sentencing set for oct 1 
sept 24 us district judge kimba wood orders presentencing 
memorandums released to the public because of the enormous interest 
in the case federal prosecutors urge her to give milken a severe 
punishment based partly on crimes milken hasnt admitted defense 
attorneys ask wood to consider only the six charges in his guilty 
plea and urge her to sentence him to community service 
sept 27 wood delays milkens sentencing to hold an 
extraordinary twoweek hearing in midoctober to consider the 
governments array of unproven charges against him she says the 
purpose of the hearing is to gain a greater insight into milkens 
character in order to fashion a fair sentence 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

