<TEXT>
a federal judge has delayed sentencing michael 
milken until she holds an extraordinary inquiry based on a broad 
array of unproven charges against the fallen junkbond financier 
us district judge kimba m wood said in her surprise ruling 
thursday that the purpose of the hearing which lawyers called a 
first in a whitecollar crime case would be to gain a greater 
understanding of milken described as a conniving crook by 
prosecutors and a contrite philanthropist by his defense 
the judge had been scheduled to pronounce milkens sentence 
monday closing a major chapter in wall streets worst scandal he 
faces a maximum 28 years imprisonment after pleading guilty to six 
felonies in april 
but as the judgment day approached federal prosecutors sought 
to persuade wood that milkens crimes are far more extensive and 
should be taken into account as she deliberates his punishment 
defense attorneys argued she should sentence milken only on the 
charges hes admitted 
wood said in ordering the sentencing hearing that it would be 
held for approximately two weeks sometime next month and structured 
to allow each side to present testimony and evidence supporting 
their positions 
federal law allows her to consider any information about a 
defendant in determining an appropriate sentence 
her ruling immediately raised the prospect of an unofficial 
trial for milken extending what his lawyers called a painful 
ordeal for the fallen pioneer of highyield bond trading at drexel 
burnham lambert inc 
i was hoping we could dispense with this his lead attorney 
arthur liman said such a hearing he told the judge could 
prolong an extraordinary anguish and agony for my clients 
family 
on the other hand the hearing could provide an opportunity for 
milkens defense team to at last confront ivan f boesky the 
convicted speculator who first implicated milken in a maze of 
financial corruption in 1986 
ill finally get to try this case after four years liman 
told reporters later outside the courtroom 
the judge tentatively scheduled a conference between the 
prosecutors and milkens lawyers tuesday to further define the 
extent of the hearing it was unclear when milken would be 
sentenced 
wood made her decision after reading voluminous presentencing 
memorandums from both the prosecution and defense she ordered them 
released this week in censored form deleting incriminating 
references to milken associates 
the judge also has received hundreds of letters both supporting 
and denouncing milken by far the biggest figure to fall in the 
wall street securities fraud scandal that has snared a number of 
whitecollar executives 
wood who at 46 is the youngest judge in the manhattan federal 
court has proceeded with extreme caution in the milken case her 
first nationally prominent sentencing decision since she was 
appointed two years ago lawyers said her ruling thursday reflected 
this concern 
she wants to give both sides an opportunity to explore matters 
in their sentencing memorandums said ira l sorkin a prominent 
securities attorney and former federal prosecutor i think she 
wants to make as complete a record as possible because the 
sentencing process is very difficult at best 
in what appeared to be a small victory for milkens defense the 
judge also made it clear she has rejected an argument by 
prosecutors that milkens sentence should be longer than the 
threeyear term of boesky who pleaded guilty to a single felony 
and paid 100 million in fines 
wood further revealed she has rejected an assertion by 
prosecutors that milken became exceedingly charitable only after 
the government began investigating him her own probation 
department report she said showed milken has been charitable for 
many years as the defense has argued 
