<TEXT>
the persian gulf crisis and its negative 
impact on east european economies has sent the viennese stock 
market into a tailspin after two years of outperforming other 
european bourses 
from an alltime high of 73921 points on march 13 the 
exchanges boersenkammer index slumped to a low of 46468 this 
week 
and since aug 1 the day before iraq invaded kuwait and sent 
oil prices rocketing and international markets reeling the index 
has been europes worst casualty off 35 percent 
viennas bourse had seen record levels of growth for two years 
as investors were attracted by strong economic growth low 
inflation and changes in eastern europe 
daily turnover rocketed from 20 million schillings 18 
million a day in early 1988 to a peak this year of 12 billion 
schillings 109 million 
some traders say prices were too high and now that world bourses 
are crashing its not surprising vienna was hardest hit 
the market was driven up partly by fantasies about making 
money in eastern europe and vienna was seen as the center for 
that now that fantasy has gone said one stock trader at a 
leading austrian bank speaking on condition of anonymity 
vienna the old capital of the austrohungarian empire is still 
considered the center of economic activity for eastern europe it 
has a long tradition as a hub for other major cities and regions in 
the area is centrally located and has all of the transportation 
and communications links needed for business activity 
higher oil prices from the gulf crisis are hitting east european 
countries hard just as they are grappling with the difficult task 
of switching to freer markets 
romanian officials for example estimate the gulf crisis has 
cost their country nearly 3 billion 
iraq was to pay 70 percent of its 17 billion debt to bucharest 
in oil but payment has been frozen the recent rise in oil prices 
to 38 a barrel will cost the economy another 770 million 
moscow is now selling oil at market prices for hard cash 
meaning eastern europe can no longer count on receiving soviet 
crude at regulated prices or in barter trade for chickens or 
trucks 
in czechoslovakia gasoline prices have risen 50 percent this 
year mainly because the soviets slashed crude supplies by 15 
percent hungary has also upped prices after moscow interrupted 
supplies 
some analysts noted that investors had begun losing interest in 
eastern europe even before the gulf crisis 
people had already begun to realize after initial euphoria 
that profits wouldnt be flowing so ast out of the east said 
josef oswald chief analyst at creditanstalt bank 
but he stressed that austrias economic growth at 45 percent 
this year and a likely 375 percent to 4 percent in 1991 is still 
stronger than the european average inflation is only at 32 
percent 
