<TEXT>
a bumper vegetable crop is rotting in the fields 
as the first fall frost approaches and muscovites fearing a hungry 
winter have joined soldiers and schoolchildren trying to rescue 
potatoes 
some people have become so desperate they are stealing potatoes 
carrots pickles and preserves from individually owned vegetable 
cellars in the villages surrounding moscow soviet media report 
the komsomolskaya pravda newspaper quoted one elderly russian 
peasant woman as saying if my memory doesnt fail me that only 
happened before the famine of 47 alas this is a really bad 
sign 
soviet prime minister nikolai ryzhkov admits that at best only 
onethird of the vegetable crop has been harvested so far and 
soviet media said thursday only a fraction of that has made its way 
to moscow warehouses and markets 
a hungry winter is coming the official tass news agency 
predicted it is unprecedented in the history of the soviet union 
in the last week of september that only 37 percent of the potatoes 
needed for moscow this winter are in storage in the city 
potatoes are a mainstay of the soviet diet known as second 
bread after the other staple that also was in short supply this 
summer for the first time since the early 1960s 
if potatoes disappear from the counter this will be a 
catastrophe for the pensioners students and poor people 
komsomolskaya pravda said 
the soviet union annually loses 20 percent to 30 percent of its 
food harvest on the way to market this years problems have been 
compounded by bad weather and fuel shortages for farm machinery 
moscowarea farms have been drenched with twice the average 
rainfall in the first two weeks of september and farmers complain 
their antiquated harvesting machines no longer work in the muddy 
fields 
students and soldiers were drafted into the harvest weeks ago 
and last week leaders of moscows regional government invited city 
dwellers to go to collective and state farms to dig potatoes for 
their own use 
in an indication how desperate the situation has become defense 
minister dmitri yazov told the soviet legislature on wednesday that 
23000 soldiers based in the moscow region are helping to dig 
potatoes 
individuals are entitled to keep every sixth sack of potatoes 
they dig or pay about 20 cents per pound for their entire bounty 
two more weeks of such weather and the whole potato crop 
will perish said the head of the moscow regional government 
department responsible for vegetable and fruit production 
it has been under water for two months already and it is 
becoming rotten not only combines but also digging machines 
cant move along the fields so the only two instruments we have 
are hands and shovel the official l yegan told moskovksy 
komsomolets newspaper 
he said at least three days of clear weather followed by two 
weeks without heavy rain were needed to salvage the harvest 
otherwise we can cross it out 
the council of ministers the soviet cabinet adopted a 
resolution on tuesday to step up the harvest effort it said bad 
weather poor management lack of discpline and lack of cooperation 
between urban and rural governments had created a real threat 
that a sizeable part of the harvest may be lost 
the resolution would send blue and whitecollar workers to work 
on farms even if it meant the suspension of some urban businesses 
and further enlistment of armed forces help in harvesting and 
transportation the resolution also directed police to step up 
antiprofiteering and antisabotage efforts it was not clear when 
the resolution would take effect 
the dmitrov city council near moscow took an even more drastic 
step declaring a state of emergency it ordered at least 20 
percent of factory workers at least half the scientific workers 
and up to 70 percent of administrators and its own executive 
committee workers to assist the harvest 
